In 2004, in an attempt to resolve this confusion, the World Society of the ACS (WSACS) was convened and an international consensus statement was published. This consensus statement defined IAH as intra-abdominal pressure (IAP) of 12 mm Hg or more in 3 readings 4 to 6 hours apart, or an abdominal perfusion pressure (APP) of 60 mm Hg or less in a minimum of 2 standardized measurements 1 to 6 hours apart, keeping in mind that an IAP <20 mm Hg is rarely clinically pathologic.5 Intra-abdominal hypertension was previously graded by Burch6 and characterized by Meldrum et al based on a prospective trial.7 The WSACS defined ACS as end organ failure (hypotension, renal dysfunction, ventilatory failure, or intestinal ischemia) in the setting of sustained IAP of 20 mm Hg or more5 (Table 1
). Primary ACS occurs in the setting of abdominal pathology, as a consequence of surgery, intestinal ischemia/edema, or traumatic insult. Secondary ACS is the development of ACS in the absence of primary abdominal pathology, usually due to capillary leak, fluid resuscitation, or sepsis. Recurrent ACS is the one that redevelops after the treatment of either primary or secondary ACS (Table 2
).5,8,9
